You can look at closures same as at functions. In Swift closure and functions have a same type. But functions have names and do not capture variables in around scope.  
You wrote a short syntax of a closure, in a complete syntax a closure has list of parameters, capture list, and return value. The complete syntax is too verbose: 

    { [weak self] (a : AClass) -&gt; BClass in
    
      return BClass()
    }
You can omit the return type, parameters types, and capture list, compiler infer it via context.    
By default, a closure captures variables by strong references for classes, and by references for structures (you can modify value of structure&#39;s instances from closure).

    var s = Struct()
    let closure = {
      s.a = 5;
    }
    closure()

About async calling of closures 
&gt; A closure is said to escape a function when the closure is passed as
&gt; an argument to the function, but is called after the function returns.

This means that the closure will have strong references for all variables that is mentioned in the closures body. To avoid strong references with self, I use next trick:

    let closure = { [weak self] () -&gt; Void in
     guard let self = self else {
      return
     }
     //do some work
    }

Look at closures as at functions without name or as at functor (in term of C++) that is created by a compiler and all will be ok.

[Here][1] you can read about syntaxes of closures. Also closures in swift same with blocks in Objective-C, and lambdas in C++.


  [1]: https://docs.swift.org/swift-book/LanguageGuide/Closures.html

